05935nam a22007335i 9780773563704DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19931993xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735637047 a10.1515/97807735637042doi  a(DE-B1597)655217  a(OCoLC)1394872988  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aRC537bF23 1993eb 7aPSY0000002bisacsh04a616.85/271 aCappeliez, Philippe, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDepression and the Social Environment :bResearch and Intervention with Neglected Populations /cRobert J. Flynn, Philippe Cappeliez. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1993] 4c©1993  a1 online resource (448 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables -- tFigures -- tAcknowledgments -- tContributors -- tAn Integrative Cognitive-Environmental View of Depression -- tChildhood Depression -- tAdolescent Depression -- tSuicidal Behaviour and Depression in Young Adults -- tGender, Psychosocial Factors, and Depression -- tDepression in General Practice Attenders -- tEffect of Unemployment on Depressive Affect -- tDepression in Canadian Native Indians -- tDepression among Immigrants and Refugees -- tDepression among People with Physical Disabilities -- tDepression in Caregivers of Impaired Elderly Family Members -- tDepression in Elderly Persons: Prevalence, Predictors, and Psychological Intervention -- tMediators of Depression in Community-Based Elders*† -- tImplications for Assessment, the Understanding of Social Etiology, and Intervention -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe authors of the essays in Depression and the Social Environment explore the etiological role of the social environment, suggesting that for "neglected populations" -- immigrants and refugees, native Indians, the unemployed, the physically disabled, the elderly, caregivers of the impaired elderly, children and adolescents, and women -- depression has significant environmental roots. These populations and the manifestations of depression that they exhibit have been largely overlooked because the importance of the social environment itself has been insufficiently investigated. The contributors of most of the essays discuss empirical findings and, taken together, provide a unique in-depth review and analysis of the international literature on etiology, intervention, and policy implications. The approach developed in this volume has obvious significance for other mental health problems with social-environmental roots. In bridging the academic/practice divide, the authors address the interrelated concerns of researchers, practitioners, and policy makers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPSYCHOLOGY / General.2bisacsh1 aArmstrong, Harvey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnes, Gordon E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoulos, Carolyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCappeliez, Philippe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFleming, Jan E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlynn, Robert J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aFlynn, Robert J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedland, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFry, Prem S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanigan, Doris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKutcher, Stan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 